Mitochondrial ubiquitin landscape in neurons

Marek Gierlinski

23 November, 2020

Collaborators: Miratul Muqit

Data

Data came from quantitative diGlycine (diGly) capture proteomics to identify Parkin-dependent ubiquitylation. The experiment was carried out in two conditions, unstimulated/basal (UT) and stimulated/depolarised (AO) in five replicates each. The total proteome was also analysed.

There are 5,616 sites on 2,229 individual proteins in the diGly data. There are 6,255 proteins in the total proteome data.

Databases

MitoCarta

We use MitoCarta 3.0 to identify mitochondrial proteins. This database contains 1,136 genes, located it the following subcompartments:

We identify E2 and E3 using UbiHub. We have the following numbers of enzymes and ligases in this database:

type n
E2 40
E3 complex 155
E3 simple 165

Results

Differential expression

Proteomics data came with Welch’s t-test p-values and fold changes. I am not sure if these are corrected for multiple tests.

Here, we re-do differential expression analysis using a more sophisticated tool, limmma and making sure that p-values are corrected for multiple tests. limma borrows information across features (sites) in order to moderate variance. We also normalise each ratio to its median. The raw data medians are close, but not equal to one, so this step reduces variance between replicates slightly and improves power of the test.

Result is not very different from the original Welch’s tests. Without the normalisation step, the numbers of significant sites (diGly) is very similar. With normalisation and using limma, we get 3,206 statistically significant sites. The Welch’s p-value gives 2,719 DE sites. The difference is mostly due to normalisation step.

This figure shows a volcano plot. Black points indicate data present in MitoCarta. The dashed horizontal line shows the significance limit, FDR = 0.05.

Identity of ubiquitylated proteins

Since we do not have sub-compartment data yet (it will come with MitoCarta 3.0), we can only identify which ubiquitilated proteins are in the MitoCarta database. However, these are already identified in the Excel file.

As we want proteins in basal state, we select only diGly proteins that are detected in the total proteome. This gives us 2,017 proteins. Out of these, there are 126 diGly proteins in MitoCarta database. None of them is E2 or E3.

This table shows the number of diGly proteins associated with each sub-compartment in MitoCarta:

Changing sites

The next figure shows how individual sites in each protein change upon stimulation. Only diGly proteins present in MitoCarta are shown. Ubiquitylation sites are simply indexed 1, 2, 3,… from the smallest to the largest position in the protein. White fill indicates non-significant change (FDR > 0.05).

iNeurons

We use iNeurons data from file mmc2.xlsx spreadsheet Kgg Quant NGN2 (AAVS) - WCL. We select protein sites marked as Significant WT 6h vs UT or Significant WT 2h vs UT.
